resources.string:
This one is a completely undocumented feature, even Android Studio reports that the <blink> tag doesn't exist (yet it DOES). I only knew about it thanks to [[jokes-and-humour-in-the-public-android-api|this blog post]], where it is explained that this 'feature' was added in a [[commit]] in 2011 with the description: "Improve LayoutInflater's compliance. There are standards, we should do our best to implement them properly.".
The exact code nowadays is slightly different, but the check and the class still persists:

...
private static final String TAG_1995 = "blink";
...
if (name.equals(TAG_1995)) {
 // Let's party like it's 1995!
 return new BlinkLayout(context, attrs);
}

The BlinkLayout class is private, so you can only use it by inflating an xml layout with a <blink> component.
This layout class will then make the text blink with a period of 500ms (0.5s visible, 0.5s invisible, repeat). And, additionally, the internal constant that the class uses to manage the logic is defined as 0x42! Blinking is truly [[42|the answer to life, the universe and everything]].
